Git and GitHub
	--Git is a version control tool that keeps track your file(s) and stores different versions of it.
	--GitHub ia a platform for colloborative remote storage.

Git's Architecture
	--It's primarily consists of 2 components.
	--One being the remote repo and the other being the local repo.

Local Repo => A repo, which you would be considering as 'working directory'.
Remote Repo => A repo that resides inside the cloud, where changes from local repo will be pushed onto.

Once, you have done your work on the 'working directory' and confident that everything can be saved now, you will be moving with the next stage of git workflow
That's Staging.

Here, you can review your changes and once be very confident, you commit all those changes to the 'local repo'.
	--This commit would be stored as a version in your project's history.
	
Run 'git status' to know, what's the status difference between the local repo and the remote repo.

Note: If you have created a new file/folder inside the working directory (local repo) and run the git status command, you will be seeing a status 'untracked'.
		--To move all changes (creation, deletion, modification) to the staging area use 'git add -all' or 'git status -a'
			--The above add comments wil stage the changes that had  happened across the entire working directory.
		--'git add .' will only stage changes that have had happened only in the specific directory, you're in currently.
		--'git add *' will stage only new and modified files and folders.
		--to unstage the changes at the staging area, use 'git reset'.
			--There are two types of unstages.
				--git reset will unstage the staged changes and changes the file to the last commit state, if we are talking about file modification.
				--if we are talking about file deletion, git reset will only unstage the deletion, it wouldn't bring back the file to the working dir, to do that use git reset --hard
		
'git reset HEAD~' can revert back a commit, straight to the working directory.
	--You then needs to re-stage it and re-commit it.
	
You can delete a file, stage the deletion.
	--To avoid all this hassle, try git rm <file_name>
	
Assume you have modified a file in your working directory and without commiting it, if you try to delete it, you would be thrown with an error.

To view the commit log use the command, 'git log'.

