Git FETCH vs Git PULL
	--FETCH, fetches the changes from remote repo and stores it into your system memory, but won't be reflected in the working dir/local repo.
	--PULL = FETCH + MERGE.
	
GIT RESTORE.
	--Helps you revert any file/folder to it's previous commit state. 
	(Either from a current commit or from the current un-commited changes.)
	--Different versions of git restore.
		--git restore <file name> ==> to restore a file.
		--git restore <directory name> ==> to restore every file within a directory.
		--git restore . ==> restore all files in the working directory to it's previous state.
		
GIT Branching
	--Instead of working directly in the main branch (which is a project's central line of development), you would be creating and working on feature and development branches.
	--Once the testing and development is done on the feature/development branch, you merge it with the main branch.
	--Merging = Combining changes from multiple branches into one.
	--In the example shown, the development and the main had changes and both had been commited.
		--Now 1st main branch has to be merged with development.
			--git merge main -m "Merging main into development"
		--Now checkout to the main branch, do the same.
			--git merge main -m "Merging development into main"
	--Sometimes, during merge, conflicts may occur.
		--MERGE CONFLICT = same part of the same file have been changed in two seperate branches.
	--MERGE CONFLICT(s) have to be resolved manually.
